\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Uh, yes'm." He trotted off.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 They passed by the jigsaw walls of the Farhahal Quadrant. A wealthy ancient had become obsessed with the notion that as long as his estate was unfinished, he would not himself finish\emdash 
that is, die. Whenever an addition neared completion, he ordered up more. Eventually the tangle of rooms, runways, vaults, bridges and gardens became an incoherent motley stuck into every cranny of th
e original, rather simple design. When Farhahal eventually did "finish," a tower half built, bickering by his heirs and lawyerly plundering of the estate for their fees brought the quadrant low. Now it was a fetid warren, visited only by the predatory and
 the unwary.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
The Specials pulled in tight and the captain urged them to get into a robo. Hari grudgingly agreed. Dors had the concentrated look that meant she was worried. They sped in silence through shadowy tunnels. There were two stops and in the brillia
ntly lit stations Hari saw rats scurrying for shelter as the pod eased to a halt. He silently pointed them out to Dors.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Brrrr," she said. "One would think that at the very center of the Empire we could eliminate pests."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Not these days," Hari said, though he suspected the rats had thrived even at the height of Empire. Rodents cared little for grandeur.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I suppose they've been our eternal companions," Dors said somberly. "No world is free of them."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "In these tunnels, the long-distance pods fly so fast that occasionally rats get sucked into the air-breathing engines."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Dors said uneasily, "That could damage the engines, even crash the pods."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "No holiday for the rat, either."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 They passed through a Sector whose citizens}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 abhorred sunlight, even the wan splashes w
hich came down through the layers by radiance tubes. Historically, Dors told him, this had arisen from fears of its ultraviolet component, but the phobia seemed to go deeper than a mere health issue.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Their pod slowed and passed along a high ramp above open
, swarming vaults. No natural light shafts brought illumination, only artificial phosphor glows. The Sector was officially named Kalanstromonia, but its citizens were known worldwide as Spooks. They seldom traveled, and their bleached faces stood out in c
rowds. Gazing down at them, they looked to Hari like swarms of grubs feeding on shadowy decay.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The Imperial Zonal Reception was inside a dome in the Julieen Sector. He and Dors entered with the Specials, who then gave way to five men and women wearing utter
ly inconspicuous business dress. These nodded to Hari and then appeared to forget him, moving down a broad rampway and chatting with each other.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 A woman at the grand doorway made too much of his entrance. Music descended around him in a sound cloud, an arr
angement of the Streeling Anthem blended subtly with the Helicon Symphony. This attracted attention from the crowds below\emdash 
exactly what he did not want. A protocol team smoothly took the handoff from the door attendants, escorting him and Dors to a balcony. He was happy for the chance to look at the view.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 From the peak of the dome the vistas were startlin
g. Spirals descended to plateaus so distant he could barely make out a forest and paths. The ramparts and gardens there had drawn millennia of spectators, including, a guide told him, 999,987 suicides, all carefully tabulated through many centuries.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Now that the number approached a million, the guide went on with relish, attempts occurred nearly}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 every hour. A man had been stopped just short of leaping that very day, wearing a gaudy holosuit programmed to flash I MADE THE MILLION after he struck.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "They seem so eager," the guide concluded with what seemed to Hari a kind of pride.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Well," Hari remarked, trying to get rid of the man, "suicide is the most sincere form of self-criticism."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The guide nodded wisely, unperturbed, and added, "Also, it does give them something to contribute to. That must be a consolation."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The protocol team had, all planned out for him, an orbit through the vast reception. Meet X, greet Y, bow to Z.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Say nothing about the Judena Zone crisis," an aide insisted. This was easy, since he had never heard of it.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The appetite-enhancers were excellent, the food that followed even better (or seemed so, which was the point of the enhancers), and he took a stim offered by a gorgeous woman.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You could get through this entire evening just nodding and smiling and agreeing with people," Dors said after the first half hour.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "It's tempting to do just that," Hari whispered as they followed the protocol lieutenant to the next bunch of Zonal figures. The air in the vast, foggy dome was freighted with negotiat
ions advanced and bargains struck.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
The Emperor arrived with full pomp. He would pay the traditional hour's tribute, then by ancient custom leave before anyone else was permitted to. Hari wondered if the Emperor ever wanted to linger in the middle of an int
eresting conversation. Cleon was well schooled in emperorhood, though, so the issue probably never came up. Cleon greeted Hari effusively, kissed Dors' hand, and then seemed to lose interest in them within two minutes, moving on}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 with his entourage to another circle of expectant faces.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari's next group proved different. Not the usual mix of diplomats, aristos, and anxious brownclad assistants, his lieutenant told him, but high figures. "People with punch," the man whispered.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 A large, muscular man was holding forth at the center of a circle, a dozen faces raptly following his every word. The protocol lieutenant tried to whisk them past, but Hari stopped her. "That's ..."}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Betan Lamurk, sir."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Knows how to hold a crowd."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Indeed, sir. Would you like a formal introduction?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "No, just let me listen."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 It was always a good idea to size up an opponent before he knew he was being watched. Hari's father had taught him that trick, just before his first matheletic competition. Such techni
ques had not managed to save his father, but they worked in the milder groves of academe.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Black hair invaded his broad brow like a pincer attack, two pointed wedges reaching down to nearly the end of his eyebrows. His hooded eyes were widely spaced and bla
zed intently from a rigging of mirth wrinkles. A slender nose seemed to point to his proudest feature, a mouth assembled from varying parts. The lower lip curled in full, impudent humor. The upper, thin and muscular, curled downward in a curve that verged
 on a sneer. A viewer would know the upper lip could overrule the lower at any moment, shifting mood abruptly\emdash a disquieting effect which could not have been bettered if he had designed it himself.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari realized quickly that, of course, Lamurk had.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lamurk was discussing some detail of interZonal trade in the Orion spiral arm, a hot issue before the High Council at the moment. Hari cared nothing}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 about trade, except as a variable in stochastic equations, so he simply watched the man's manner.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 To underline a poi
nt Lamurk would raise his hands over his head, fingers open, voice rising. Then, his point made, his voice evened out and he lowered them to chest height, held precisely side by side. As his well-modulated voice became deeper and more reflective, he moved
 the hands apart. Then\emdash voice rising again\emdash his hands soared to head level and windmilled one around the other, the subject now complex, the listener thereby commanded to pay close attention.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He kept close eye contact with the whole audience, a piercing gaze sweeping the circle. A last point, a quick touch of humor, grin flashing, sure of himself\emdash a pause for the next question.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He finished his point with, "\emdash and for some of us, 'Pax Imperium' looks more like Tax Imperium,' eh?" Then he saw Hari. A quick furrowin
g of his brow, then, "Academician Seldon! Welcome! I'd been wondering when I was going to get to meet you."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Don't let me interrupt your, ah, lecture."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 This provoked some titters and Hari saw that to accuse a member of the High Council of pontificating was a mild social jab. "I found it fascinating."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Pretty humdrum stuff, I'm afraid, compared to you mathists," Lamurk said cordially.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I am afraid my mathematics is even more dry than Zonal trade."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 More titters, though this time Hari could not quite see why.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I just try to separate out the factions," Lamurk said genially. "People treat money like it is a religion."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 This gained him some agreeing laughter. Hari said, "Fortunately, there are no sects in geometry."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "We're just trying to get the best deal for the whole Empire, Academician."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "The best is the enemy of the good, I'd imagine."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I suppose then, you'll be applying mathematical logic to our problems on the Council?" Lamurk's voice remained friendly, but his eyes took on a veiled character. "Assuming you gain a ministership?"}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Alas, so far as the laws of mathematics are sharp and certain, they do not refer to reality. So far as they refer to reality, they are not certain."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
Lamurk glanced at the crowd, which had grown considerably. Dors grasped Hari's hand and he realized from her squeeze that this had somehow turned into something important. He could not see why, but there was no time to size up the situation.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lamurk said, "Then this psychohistory thing I hear about, it's not useful?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Not to you, sir," Hari said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lamurk's eyes narrowed, but his affable grin remained. "Too tough for us?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Not ready for use, I'm afraid. I don't have the logic of it yet."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lamurk chuckled, beamed at the still growing crowd, and said jovially, "A logical thinker!\emdash what a refreshing contrast with the real world."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 General laughter. Hari tried to think of something to say. He saw one of his bodyguards block a man nearby, inspect something in the man's suit, then let him go.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Y'see, Academician, on the High Council we can't be spending our time on theory." Lamurk paused for effect, as though making a campaign speech. "We've got to be just.. . and sometimes, folks, we've got to be hard."}
{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari raised an eyebrow. "My father used to say, 'It's a hard man who's only just, and a sad man who's only wise.'"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 A few ooohs in the crowd told him he had scored a hit. Lamurk's eyes confirmed the cut.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Well, we do try on the Council, we do. No doubt we
 can use some help from the learned quarters of the Empire. I'll have to read one of your books, Academician." He shot a look with raised eyebrows at the crowd. "Assuming 1 can."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari shrugged. "I will send you my monograph on transfinite geometric calculus."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Impressive title," Lamurk said, eyes playing to the audience.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "It's the same with books as with men\emdash a very small number play great parts; the rest are lost in the multitude."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "And which would you rather be?" Lamurk shot back.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Among the multitudes. At least I wouldn't have to attend so many receptions."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 This got a big laugh, surprising Hari. Lamurk said, "Well, I'm sure the Emperor won't tire you out with too much socializing. But you'll get invited everywhere. You've got a sharp tongue on you, Academician."}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "My father had another saying, too. 'Wit is like a razor. Razors are more likely to cut those who use them when they've lost their edge.'"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
His father had also told him that in a public trade of barbs, the one who lost temper first lost the exchange. He had not recalled that until this instant. Hari remembered too late that Lamurk was known for his humor in High Council meetings. Probably scr
ipted for him; certainly he displayed none here.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 A quick tightening of the cheeks spread into a bloodless white line of lip. Lamurk's features twisted into an expression of distaste\emdash not a long way to go, for most of them\emdash 
and he gave an ugly, wet laugh.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The crowd stood absolutely silent. Something had happened.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Ah, there are other people who would like to meet}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 the Academician," Hari's lieutenant said, sliding neatly into the growing, awkward silence.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari shook hands, murmured meaningless pteas-antries, and let himself be whisked away.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He had another stim to calm himself. Somehow he was more jittery afterward than during the social collision. Lamurk had given Hari a cold, angry stare as they parted.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I'll keep track of him," Dors said. "You just enjoy your fame."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 To Hari this was a flat impossibility, but he tried. Seldom did one see such a variety of people, and he calmed himself by lapsing into a habitual role: polite observer. It was not as though th
e usual social chitchat demanded much concentration. A warm smile would do most of the work for him here.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The party was a microcosm of Trantorian society. In spare moments, Hari watched the social orders interact.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Cleon's grandfather had reinstated many Ru
ellian traditions, and one of those customs required that members of all five classes be present at any grand Imperial function. Cleon seemed especially keen on this practice, as if it would raise his popularity among the masses. Hari kept his own doubts 
private.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 First and obvious came the gentry\emdash the inherited aristocracy. Cleon himself stood at the apex of a pyramid of rank that descended from the Imperium to mighty Quadrant Dukes and Spiral Arm Princes, past}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Life Peers, all the way down to the local barons Hari used to know back on Helicon.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Working in the fields, he had seen them pompously scudding overhead. Each governed a domain no larger than they could cross by flitter in a day. To a member of the gentry, life was busy with the Great Game\emdash 
a ceaseless campaign to advance the fortunes of one's noble house, arranging greater status for your family line through political alliances, or marriages for your many children.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari snorted in derision, masking it by taking another stim. He had studied anthropological reports from a thousand Fallen Worlds\emdash 
those that had devolved in isolation, reverting to cruder ways of life. He knew this pyramid-shaped order to be among the most natural and enduring human social patterns. Even when a planet was reduced to simple agri
culture and hand-forged metals, the same triangular format endured. People liked rank and order.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The endless competition of gentry families had been the first and easiest psychohistorological system Hari ever modeled. He had first combined basic game theor
y and kin selection. Then, in a moment of inspiration, he inserted them into the equations that described sand grains skidding down the slopes of a dune. That correc}{\fs20 tl}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
y described sudden transitions: social slippages.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 So it was with the rise and fall of noble family lines. Long, smooth eras\emdash then abrupt shifts.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He watched the crowd, picking out those in the second aristocracy, supposedly equal to the first: the meritocracy.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 As department chairman at a major Imperial university, Hari was himself a lord in that hierarchy\emdash  a pyramid of achievement rather than of birth. Meritocrats had entirely different obsessions than}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 the gentry's constant dynastic bickerings. In fact, few in Hari's class bothered to breed at all, so busy were they in their chosen fields. Gentry
 jostled for the top ranks of Imperial government, while second tier meritocrats saw themselves wielding the real power.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 If only Clean had such a role in mind for me, Hari thought. A vice minister position, or an advisory post. He could have managed that f
or a time, or else bungled it and got himself forced out of office. Either way, he would be safe back at Streeling within a year or two. They don't execute vice ministers . . . not for incompetence, at least.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Nor did a vice minister feel the worst burden of rule\emdash bearing responsibility for the lives of a quadrillion human beings.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Dors saw him drifting along in his own thoughts. Under her gentle urging, he sampled tasty savories and made small talk.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The gentry could be distinguished by their ostentatiously fashionable clothing, while the economists, generals and other meritocrats tended to wear the formal garb of their professions.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 So he was making a political statement, after all, Hari realized. In wearing professor's robes, he emphasized that there might be a non-gentry First Minister for the first time in forty years.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Not that he minded making that statement. Hari just wished he had done it on purpose.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Despite the official Ruellian ethos, the remaining three social classes seemed nearly invisible at the party.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
The factotums wore somber costumes of brown or gray, with expressions to match. They seldom spoke on their own. Usually they hovered at the elbow of some aristo, supplying facts and even figures that the more gaily-dressed guests used in their arguments
. Aristos}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
