\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Already the Empire had worlds, Zones, and even whole arcs of spiral arms descended into squalor. Still worse, in a way, was a steady slide into garish amusements, even vulgarity. The media swarmed with th
e stuff. The new "renaissance" styles from worlds like Sark were popular.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 To Hari the best of the Empire was its strands of restraint, of subtlety and discretion in manners,}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 finesse and charm, intelligence, talent, }{\fs20 an}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 d even glamour. Helicon had been crude and rural, but }{\fs20 it}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 knew the difference between silk and sw}{\fs20 i}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 ne.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "What do the policy types say?" Yugo sat }{\fs20 halfw}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 ay on Hari's desk, avoiding the control }{\fs20 functions }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
implanted beneath a woody veneer. He had come }{\fs20 in }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 with the kaff as a pretext, fishing for gossip about th}{\fs20 e }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 exalted. Hari smiled to himself; people relished s}{
\fs20 om}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 e aspects of hierarchy, however much they griped about it.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "They're hoping some of the 'moral rebirth' }{\fs20 move}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 ments\emdash like revised Ruellianism, say\emdash w}{\fs20 ill}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033  take }{\fs20 h}{
\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 old. Put spine into the Zones, one of them said.*}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Ummm. Think it'll work?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Not for long."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Ideology was an uncertain cement. Even }{\fs20 religion }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 fervor could not glue an empire together for }{\fs20 lon}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
g. Either force could drive formation of an empire, b}{\fs20 u}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 t they could not hold against greater, steady rides\emdash  principally, economics.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "How about the war in the Orion Zone?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Nobody mentioned it."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Think we've got war figured right in the equations?" Yugo had a knack for suddenly putting his finger on what was bothering Hari.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "No. War was an overesteemed element in history."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Certainly war often gained center stage; no one continued to read a beautiful poem when a fist fight broke out nearby. But fist fights did not last, either. Further, they joggled the elbows of those trying 
to make a living. To engineers and traders alike, war did not pay. So why did wars break out now, with all the economic weight of the Empire against them?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Wars are simple. But we're missing something basic\emdash I can feel it."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "We've based the matrices on all that historical}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 data Dors dug out," Yugo said a bit defensively. "That's solid."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I don't doubt it. Still. .."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Look, we've got over twelve thousand years of hard facts. I built the model on that."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I have a feeling what we're missing isn't subtle."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Most collapses were not from abstruse causes. In the early days of Empire consolidation, local minor sovereignties flourished, then died. There were recurrent themes in their histories.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Again and again, star-spanning realms collapsed under the weight of excessiv
e taxation. Sometimes the taxes supported mercenary armies which defended against neighbors, or which simply kept domestic order against centrifugal forces. Whatever the ostensible cause of taxes, soon enough the great cities became depopulated, as people
 fled the tax collectors, seeking "rural peace."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 But why did they do that spontaneously?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "People." Hari sat up suddenly. "That's what we're missing."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Huh? You proved yourself\emdash remember? the Reductionist Theorem?\emdash that individuals don't matter."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "They don't. But people do. Our coupled equations describe them in the mass, but we don't know the critical drivers."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "That's all hidden, down in the data."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Maybe not. What if we were big spiders, instead of primates? Would psychohistory look the same?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Yugo frowned. "Well ... if the data were the same . . ."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Data on trade, wars, population statistics? It wouldn't matter whether we were counting spiders instead of people?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Yugo shook his head, his face clouding, unwilling to concede a point that might topple years of work. "It's gotta be there."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Your coming in here to get details of what the rich and famous do at their revels\emdash where's that in the equations?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Yugo's mouth twisted, irked now. "That stuff, it doesn't matter."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Who says?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Well, history\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Is written by the winners, true enough. But how do the great generals get men and women to march through freezing mud? When won't they march?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Nobody knows."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "We need to know. Or rather, the equations do."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "How?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I don't know."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Go to the historians?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari laughed. He shared Dors' contempt for most of her profession. The current fashion in the study of the past was a matter of taste, not data.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He had once thought that history was simply a matter of grubbing in musty cyberfiles. Then, if Dors would show him how to track down data\emdash 
 whether encoded in ancient ferrite cylinders or polymer blocks or strandware\emdash then he would have a firm basis for mathematics. Didn't Dors and other historians simply add one more brick of knowledge to an ever-growing monument?}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The cu
rrent style, though, was to marshal the past into a preferred flavor. Factions fought over the antiquity, over "their" history vs. "ours." Fringes flourished. The "spiral-centric" held that historical forces spread along spiral arms, whereas the "Hub-focu
sed" maintained that the Galactic Center was the true mediating agency for causes, trends, movements, evolution. Technocrats contended with Naturals, who felt that innate human qualities drove change.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Among myriad facts and footnotes, specialists saw present politics mirrored in the past. As the present}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 fractured and transfigured, there seemed no point of reference outside history itself\emdash an unreliable platform indeed, especially when one realized how ma
ny mysterious gaps there were in the records. All this seemed to Hari to be more fashion than foundation. There was no uncontested past.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 What contained the centrifugal forces of relativism\emdash let me have my viewpoint and you can have yours\emdash was an arena of bro
ad agreement. Most people generally held that the Empire was good, overall. That the long periods of stasis had been the best times, for change always cost someone. That above the competing throng, through the factions shouting what were essentially famil
y stories at each other, there was worth in comprehending where humanity had passed, what it had done.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 But there agreement stopped. Few seemed concerned with where humanity, or even the Empire, was going. He had come to suspect that the subject was ignored,
 in favor of your-history-against-mine, because most historians unconsciously dreaded the future. They sensed the decline in their souls and knew that over the horizon lay not yet another shift-then-stasis but a collapse.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "So what do we do?" Hari realized that Yugo had said this twice now. He had drifted off into reverie.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I ... don't know."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Add another term for basic instincts?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari shook his head. "People don't run on instinct. But they do behave }{\fs20 like}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033  people\emdash -like primates, I suppose."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "So ... we should look into that?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari threw up his hands. "I confess. I feel that this line of logic is leading somewhere\emdash but I can't see the end of it."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Yugo nodded, grinned. "It'll come out when it's ripe."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Thanks. I'm not the best of collaborators, I know. Too moody."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Hey, never mind. Gotta think out loud sometimes, is all."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Sometimes I'm not sure I'm thinking at all."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Lemme show you the latest, huh?" Yugo liked to parade his inventions, and Hari sat bac
k as Yugo accessed the office holo and patterns appeared in midair. Equations hung in space, 3D-stacked and each term color-coded.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 So many! They reminded Hari of birds, flocking in great banks.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Psychohistory was basically a vast set of interlocked equation
s, following the variables of history. It was impossible to change one and not vary any other. Alter population and trade changed, along with modes of entertainment, sexual mores, and a hundred other factors.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Some were undoubtedly unimportant, but which? History was a bottomless quarry of factoids, meaningless without some way of winnowing the hail of particulars. That was the essential first task of any theory of history
\emdash to find the deep variables.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Post-diction rates\emdash presto!" Yugo said, his hand computer suspending in air 3D graphs, elegantly arrayed. "Economic indices, variable-families, the works."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "What eras?" Hari asked.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Third millennia to seventh, G.E."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The multidimensional surfaces representing economic variables were like twisted bottles filled with\emdash as Yugo time-stepped them\emdash 
sloshing fluids. The liquids of yellow and amber and virulent red flowed around and through each other in a supple, slow dance. Hari was perpetually amazed at how beauty arose in the most unlikely ways from mathematics. Yugo had
 plotted abstruse econometric quantities, yet in the gravid sway of centuries they made delicate arabesques.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Surprisingly good agreement," Hari allowed. The yellow surfaces of historical data merged cleanly with the other color skins, fluids finding curved levels. "And covering four millennia! No infinities?"}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "That new renormalization scheme blotted them out."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Excellent! The middle Galactic Era data is the most solid, too, correct?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Yeah. The politicians got into the act after the seventh millennium. Dors is helpin' me filter out the garbage."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari admired the graceful blending of colors, ancient wine in transfinite bottles.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The psychohistorical rates linked together strongly. History was not at all like a sturdy steel edifice rigidly spanning time; it ra
ther more resembled a rope bridge, groaning and flexing with every footfall. This "strong coupling dynamic" led to resonances in the equations, wild fluctuations, even infinities. Yet nothing really went infinite in reality, so the equations had to be fix
ed. Hari and Yugo had spent many years eliminating ugly infinites. Maybe their goal was in sight.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "How do the results look if you simply run the equations forward, past the seventh millennium?" Hari asked.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Oscillations build up," Yugo admitted.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Feedback lo
ops were scarcely new. Hari knew the general theorem, ancient beyond measure: If all variables in a system are rightly coupled, and you can change one of them precisely and broadly, then you can indirectly control all of them. The system could be guided t
o an exact outcome through its myriad internal feedback loops. Spontaneously, the system ordered itself\emdash and obeyed.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 History, of course, obeyed no one. But for eras such as the fourth to seventh millennium, somehow}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 the equations got matters right. Psychohistory could "post-diet" history.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 In truly complex systems, how adjustments occur lay beyond the human complexity horizon, beyond knowing\emdash and most important, not worth knowing.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 But if the system went awry, somebody had to get down in the guts of it and find the trouble. "Any ideas? Clues?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Yugo shrugged. "Look at this."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The fluids lapped at the walls of the bottles. More warped volumes appeared, filled with brightly colored data-liquids. Hari watched as tides swept through the burnt-orange variable-space, driv
ing answering waves in the purple layers nearby. Soon the entire bob showed furiously churning turbulence.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "So the equations fail," Hari said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Yeah, big time, too. The grand cycles last about a hundred and twenty-five years. But smoothing out events shorter than eighty years gives a steady pattern. See\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari watched turbulence build like a hurricane churning a multicolored ocean.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Yugo said, "That takes away scatter due to 'generational styles,' Dors calls it. I can take the Zones that consciously increased human lifespan. I time-step the equations forward, great\emdash 
but then I run out of data. How come? I mine the history some, and it turns out those societies didn't last long."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari shook his head. "You're sure? I'd imagine increasing the average age would bring a little wisdom into the picture."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Not so! I looked deeper and found that when the lifespan reached the social cycle time, usually about a
 hundred and ten Standard Years, instability rose. Whole planets had wars, depressions, general social illnesses."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari frowned. "That effect\emdash is it known?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Don't think so."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "This is why humans reached a barrier in improving their longevity? Society breaks down, ending the progress?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Yeah."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Yugo wore a small, tight smile, by which Hari knew that he was rather proud of this result. "Growing irregularities, building to\emdash chaos."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 This was the deep problem they had not mastered. "Damn!" Hari had a gut dislike of unpredictability.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Yugo gave Hari a crooked smile. "On that one, boss, I got no news."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Don't worry," Hari said cheerfully, though he didn't feel it. "You've made good progress. Remember the adage\emdash the Imperium wasn't built in a day."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Yeah, but it seems to be fallin' apart plenty fast."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 They seldom mentioned the deep-seated motivation for psychohistory: the pervasive anxiety that the Empire was declining, for reasons no one kn
ew. There were theories aplenty, but none had predictive power. Hari hoped to supply that. Progress was infuriatingly slow.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Yugo was looking morose. Hari got up, came around the big desk, and gave Yugo a gentle slap on the back. "Cheer up! Publish this result."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Can I? We've got to keep psychohistory quiet."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Just group the data, then publish in a journal devoted to analytical history. Talk to Dors about selecting the journal."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Yugo brightened. "I'll write it up, show you\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "No, leave me out of it. It's your work."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Hey, you showed me how to set up the analysis, where\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "It's yours. Publish."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Well..."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari did not mention the fact that, now, anything}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 published under his name would attract attention. A few might guess at the immensely larger theory lurking behind the simple lifespan-resonance effect Best to keep a low profile.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 When Yugo had gone back to work, Hari sat for a while and watched the squalls work through the data-fluids, still time-stepping in the air above his desk. Then he glanced at a favorite 
quotation of his. pointed out to him by Dors, given to him on a small, elegant ceramo-plaque:}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Minimum force, applied at a cusp moment at the historical fulcrum, paves the path to a }{\fs20 distant }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 vision. Pursue only those immediate }{\fs20 goals which }{
