\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 THE ROSE MEETS THE SCALPEL}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 COMPUTATIONAL REPRESENTATION\emdash ... it is clear that, except for occasional 
outbursts, the taboos against advanced, artificial intelligences head throughout the Empire through the great sweep of historical time. This uniformity of cultural opinion probably reflects tragedies and traumas with artificial forms far back in pre-Empir
e
 ages. There are records of early transgressions by self-aware programs, including those by "sims," or self-organizing simulations. Apparently the pre-ancients enjoyed recreating personalities of their own past, perhaps for instruction or amusement or eve
n research. None of these are known to survive, but tales persist that they were once a high art.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Of darker implication are the narratives which hypothesize self-aware intelligences lodged in bodies resembling human. While low-order mechanical forms are cus
tomarily allowed throughout the Empire, these "tiktoks" constitute no competition with humans, since they perform only simple and often disagreeable tasks.. ..}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 \emdash ENCYCLOPEDIA GALACTICA}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 1.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Joan of Arc wakened inside an amber dream. Cool breezes caressed her, odd noises reverberated. She heard before she saw\emdash }{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 \emdash and abruptly found herself sitting outdoors. She noted things one at a time, as though some part of herself were counting them.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Soft air. Before her, a smooth round table.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Pressing against her, an unsettling white chair. Its ;eat, unlike those in her home village of Domremy, was not hand-hewn of wood. Its smooth slickness ewdly aped her contours. She reddened.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Strangers. One, two, three . .. winking into being 3efore her eyes.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 They moved. Peculiar people. She could not tell Woman from man, except for those whose pan-:aloons and tunics outlined their intimate parts. Hie spectacle was even more than she'd seen in Chinon, at the lewd court o
f the Great and True King.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Talk. The strangers seemed oblivious of her, though \bullet he could hear them chattering in the }{\fs20 background}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 as distinctly as she sometimes heard her voices. She listened only long enough to conclude that what they said, having nothing to do with holiness or France, was clearly not worth hearing.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Noise. From outside. An iron river of self-moving carriages muttered by. She felt surprise at this\emdash then somehow the emotion evaporated.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 A long view, telescoping in\emdash }{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Pearly mists concealed distant ivory spires. Fog made them seem like melting churches.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 What was this place?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 A vision, perhaps related to her beloved voices. Could such apparitions be holy?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Surely the man at a nearby table was no angel. He was eating scrambled eggs\emdash through a straw.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 And the women\emdash unchaste, flagrant, gaudy cornucopias of hip and thigh and breast. Some drank red wine from transparent goblets, different from any she'd seen at the royal court.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Others seemed to sup from floating clouds\emdash delicate, billowing mousse fogs. One mist, reeking of beef with a tangy Loire sauce, passed near her. She breathed in\emdash 
and felt in an instant that she had experienced a meal.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Was this heaven? Where appetites were satisfied without labor and toil?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 But no. Surely the final reward was not so, so ... carnal. And perturbing. And embarrassing.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The fire some sucked into their mouths from little reeds\emdash those alarmed her. A cloud of smoke drifting her way flushed birds of panic from her breast\emdash 
 although she could not smell the smoke, nor did it burn her eyes or sear her throat.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The fire, the fire! she thought, heart fluttering in panic. What had . . . ?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 She saw a being made of breastplate coming at her with a tray of food and drink\emdash poison from enemies,}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 no doubt, the foes of France! she thought in chum-ing fright\emdash she at once reached for her sword.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Be with you in a moment," the breastplated thing said as it wheeled past her to another table. "I've only got four hands. Do have patience."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 An inn, she thought. It was some kind of inn, though there appeared to be nowhere to Jodge. And yes ... it came now ... she was supposed to meet someone ... a gentleman?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 That one: the tall, skinny old man\emdash much older than Jacques Dars, her father\emdash the only one besides herself attired normally.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Something about his dress recalled the
 foppish dandies at the Great and True King's court. His hair curled tight, its whiteness set off by a lilac ribbon at his throat. He wore a pair of mignonette ruffles with narrow edging, a long waistcoat of brown satin with colored flowers, and sported r
ed velvet breeches, white stockings, and chamois shoes.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 A silly, vain aristocrat, she thought. A fop accustomed to carriages, who could not so much as sit a horse, much less do holy battle.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 But duty was a sacred obligation. If King Charles ordered her to advance, advance she would.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 She rose. Her suit of mail felt surprisingly light. She hardly sensed the belted-on protective leather flaps in front and back, nor the two metal arm plates that left elbows free to wield the sword. No one paid 
the least attention to the rustle of her mail or her faint clank.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Are you the gentleman I am to meet? Monsieur Arouet?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Don't call me that," he snapped. "Arouet is my father's name\emdash the name of an authoritarian prude. not mine. No one has called me that in years."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Up close, he seemed less ancient. She'd been }{\fs20 mislead}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033  by his white hair, which she now saw was }{\fs20 false,}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 powdered wig secured by the lilac ribbon under his chin.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "What should I call you then?" She suppressed terms of contempt for this dandy\emdash rough words learned from comrades-in-arms, now borne by demons to her tongue's edge, but not beyond.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Poet, tragedian, historian." He leaned forward and with a wicked wink whispered, "I style myself Voltaire. Freethinker. Philosopher king."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Besides the King of Heaven and His son, I call but one man King. Charles VII of the House of Valois. And I'll call you Arouet until my royal master bids me do otherwise."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "My dear pucelle, your Charles is dead."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "No!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He glanced at the noiseless carriages propelled by invisible forces on the street. "Sit down, sit down. Much else has passed, as well. Do help me get that droll waiter's attention."}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You know me?" Led by her voices, she had cast off her father's name to call herself La Pucelle, the Chaste Maid.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I know you very well
. Not only did you live centuries before me, I wrote a play about you. And I have curious memories of speaking with you before, in some shadowy spaces." He shook his head, frowning. "Besides my garments\emdash beautiful, n'est ce pas?\emdash 
you're the only familiar thing about this place. You and the street, though I must say you're younger than I thought, while the street . . . hmmm . . . seems wider yet older. They finally got 'round to paving it."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I, I cannot fathom\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He pointed to a sign that bore the inn's name\emdash Aux Deux Magots. "Mademoiselle Lecouvreur\emdash a famous actress, though equally known as my mistress." He blinked. "You're blushing\emdash how sweet."}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I know nothing of such things." She added with more than a trace of pride, "I am a maid."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He grimaced. "Why one would be proud of such an unnatural state, I can't imagine."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "As I cannot imagine why you are so dressed."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "My tailors will be mortally offended! But allow me to suggest that it is you, my dear pucelle, who, in your insistence on dressing like a man, would deprive civilized society of one of its most harmless pleasures."}
{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "An insistence I most dearly paid for," she retorted, remembering how the bishops badgered her about her male attire as relentlessly as they inquired after her divine voices.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
As if in the absurd attire members of her sex were required to wear, she could have defeated the English-loving duke at Orleans! Or led three thousand knights to victory at Jargeau and Meung-sur-Loire, Beaugency and Patay, throughout that summer of
 glorious conquests when, led by her voices, she could do no wrong.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 She blinked back sudden tears. A rush of memory\emdash }{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Defeat.. . Then the bloodred darkness of lost battles had descended, muffling her voices, while those of her English-loving enemies grew strong.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
"No need to get testy," Monsieur Arouet said, gently patting her knee plate. "Although I personally find your attire repulsive, I would defend to the death your right to dress any way you please. Or undress." He eyed the near-transparent upper garmen
t of a female inn patron nearby.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Sir\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Paris has not lost its appetite for finery after all. Pale fruit of the gods, don't you agree?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "No, I do not. There is no virtue greater than chastity in women\emdash or in men. Our Lord was chaste, as are our saints and priests."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Priests chaste!" He rolled his eyes. "Pity you weren't at the school my father forced me to attend as a boy. You could have so informed the Jesuits, who daily abused their innocent charges."}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I, I cannot believe\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "And what of him?" Voltaire talked right over her, pointing at the four-handed creature on wheels rolling toward them. "No doubt such a creature is chaste. Is it then virtuous, too?"}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Christianity, France itself, is founded on\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "If chastity were practiced in France as much as it's preached, the race would be extinct."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The wheeled creature braked by their table. Stamped on his chest was what appeared to be his name: }{\fs20 GARCON}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
 213-ADM. In a bass voice as clear as any man's, he said, "A costume party, eh? I hope my delay will not make you late. Our mechfolk are having difficulties."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 It eyed the other tiktok bringing dishes forth\emdash a honey-haired blond in a hairnet, approximately humanlike. A demon?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The Maid frowned. Its jerky glance, even though mechanical, recalle
d the way her jailers had gawked at her. Humiliated, she had cast aside the women's garments that her Inquisitors forced her to wear. Resuming manly attire, she'd scornfully put her jailers in their place. It had been a fine moment.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The cook assumed a haug
hty look, but fussed with her hairnet and smiled at Gar?on 213-ADM before averting her eyes. The import of this eluded Joan. She had accepted mechanicals in this strange place, without questioning their meaning. Presumably this was some intermediate stati
on in the Lord's providential order. But it was puzzling.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Monsieur Arouet reached out and touched the mechman's nearest arm, whose construction the Maid could not help but admire. If such a creature}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 could be made to sit a horse, in battle it would be invincible. The possibilities . . .}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Where are we?" Monsieur Arouet asked. "Or perhaps I should ask, when? I have friends in high places\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "And I in low," the mechman said good-naturedly.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "\emdash and I demand a full account of where we are, what's going on."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The mechm
an shrugged with two of his free arms, while the two others set the table. "How could a mechwait with intelligence programmed to suit his station, instruct monsieur, a human being, in the veiled mysteries of simspace? Have monsieur and mademoiselle decide
d on their order?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You have not yet brought us the menu," said Monsieur Arouet.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The mechman pushed a button under the table. Two flat scrolls embedded in the table shimmered, letters glowing. The Maid let out a small cry of delight\emdash then, in response to Mon
sieur Arouet's censorious look, clapped her hand over her mouth. Her peasant manners were a frequent source of embarrassment.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Ingenious," said Monsieur Arouet, switching the button on and off as he examined the underside of the table. "How does it work?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I'm not programmed to know. You'll have to ask a mechlectrician about that."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "A what?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "With all due respect, Monsieur, my other customers are waiting. I am programmed to take your order."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "What will you have, my dear?" Monsieur Arouet asked her.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 She looked down, embarrassed. "Order for me," she said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Ah, yes. I quite forgot."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Forgot what?" asked the mechman.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "My companion is unlettered. She can't read. I might as well be, too, for all the good this menu's doing me."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 So this obviously learned man could not fathom the Table of House. Joan found that endearing, amid this blizzard of the bizarre.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The mechman explained and Voltaire interrupted.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Cloud-food! Electronic cuisine?" He grimaced. "Just bring me the best you have for great hunger and thirst. What can you recommend for abstinent virgins\emdash 
a plate of dirt, perhaps? Chased with a glass of vinegar?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Bring me a slice of bread," the Maid said with frosty dignity. "And a small bowl of wine to dip it in."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Wine!" said Monsieur Arouet. "Your voices allow wine? Ma}{\fs20 is}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
 quelle scandale! If word got out that you drink wine, what would the priests say of the shoddy example you're setting for the future saints of France?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He turned to the mechman. "Bring her a glass of water, small." As Gar?on 213-ADM withdrew, Monsieur Arouet called out, "And make sure the bread is a crust! Preferably moldy!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 2.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Marq Hofti strode swiftly toward his Waldon Shaft office, his colleague and friend Sybyl chattering beside him. She was always energetic, bristling with ideas. Only occasionally did her energy seem tiresome.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The Artifice Associates offices loomed, weighty}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
and impressive in the immense, high shaft. A flutter-glider circled the protruding levels far above, banking among pretty green clouds. Marq craned his neck upward and watched the glider catch an updraft of the city's powerful air circulators. Atmospheric
 control even added the puff-ball vapors for variety. He longed to be up there, swooping among their sticky flavors.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Instead, he was down here, donning his usual carapace of each-day's-a-challenge vigor. And today was going to be unusual. Risky. And though 
the zest for it sang in his stride, his grin, the fear of failure gave a leaden lining to his most buoyant plans.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 If he failed today, at least he would not rumble from the sky, like a pilot who misjudged the thermals in the shaft. Grimly, he entered his office.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "It makes me nervous," Sybyl said, cutting into his mood.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Umm. What?" He dumped his pack and sat at his ornate control board.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 She sat beside him. The board filled half the office, making his desk look like a cluttered afterthought. "The Sark sims. We've spent so much time on those resurrection protocols, the slices and embeddings and all."}
{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I had to fill in whole layers missing from the recordings. Synaptic webs from the association cortex. Plenty of work."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I did, too. My Joan was missing chunks of the hippocampus."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
"Pretty tough?" The brain remembered things using constellations of agents from the hippocampus. The. laid down long-term memory elsewhere, spattering pieces of it around the cerebral cortex. Not nearly as clean and orderly as computer me
mory, which was one of the major problems. Evolution was a kludge, mechanisms crammed in here and there, with little attention}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 to overall design. At building minds, the Lord was something of an amateur.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Murder. I stayed to midnight for weeks. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Me too. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Did you... use the library?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He considered. Artifice Associates kept dense files of brain maps, all taken from volunteers. There were menus for selecting mental agents\emdash 
subroutines which could carry out the tasks which myriad synapses did in the brain. Th
ese were all neatly translated into digital equivalents, saving great labor. But to use them meant running up big bills, because each was copyrighted. "No. Got a private source. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 She nodded. "Me too. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Was she trying to coax an admission from him? They ha
d both had to go through scanning as part of getting their Master Class ratings in the meritocracy. Marq had thriftily kept his scan. Better than a back-alley brain map, for sure. He was no genius, but the basics of Voltaire's underpinnings weren't the im
portant part, after all. Exactly how the sim ran the hindbrain functions\emdash basic maintenance, housekeeping circuitry\emdash certainly couldn't matter, could it?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Let's have a look at our creations, " Marq said brightly, to get off the subject.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Sybyl shook her head. "Mine is stable. But look\emdash  we don't really know what to expect. These fully integrated Personalities are still isolated. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Nature of the beast. " Marq shrugged, playing the jaded pro. Now that his hands caressed the board, though, a tingling excitement seized him.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Let's do it today, " she said, words rushing out.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "What? I\emdash I'd like to slap some more patches over the gaps, maybe install a rolling buffer as insurance against character shifts, spy into\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Details! Look, these sims have been running on}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 internals for weeks of sim-time, self-integrating. Let's interact. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Marq thought of the glider pilot, up there amid treacherous winds. He had never done anything so risky; he wasn't the type. His kind of peril lay on the digital playing fielcj. Here, he was master.}{
