"Since when is logic simple? I cannot 'simply' compose my lettre philosophique on the absurdity of denying those like Gargon 213-ADM the rights of man on the grounds that they have no soul. He's an amusing little fellow, don't you think? And as smart as
 at least a dozen priests whom I have known. Does he not speak? Respond? Desire? He is infatuated with a human cook. Should he not be able to pursue happiness as freely as you or I? If he has no soul, then you have no soul, either. If you have a soul, it 
can only be inferred from your behavior, and since we may make the identical inference from the behavior of Garcon, so does he. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I'm inclined to agree, " Madame la Scientiste said. "Though of course 213-ADM's reactions are simulations. Self-aware machines have been illegal for millennia. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "That is what I challenge!" Voltaire shouted.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "And how much of that comes from Sarkian programming?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "None. The rights of man\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Hardly need apply to machines. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Voltaire scowled. "I cannot express myself completely freely on these sensitive matters\emdash unless you rid me of the memory of what I suffered for expressing my ideas. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "But your past is your self. Without all of it, intact\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Nonsense! The truth is, I never dared express myself freely on many matters. Take that lif
e-hating Puritan Pascal, his views of original sin, miracles, and much other nonsense besides. I didn't dare say what I really thought! Always, I had to calculate what every assault on convention and traditional stupidity would cost. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Madame la Scientiste pursed her lips prettily. "You did well enough, I would guess. You were famous. We don't know your history, or even your world. But from your memories I can tell\emdash "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "And the Maid! She is thwarted more than I! For her convictions, she paid the ultimate price. Being crucified could be no worse than what she suffered at the stake. Light a goodly pipe\emdash as I love to do\emdash 
 before her, and her eyes roll with confusion. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "But that's crucial to who she is, "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Rational inquiries cannot be carried out in an atmosphere o
f fear and intimidation. If our contest is to be fair, I implore you, rid us of these terrors that prevent us from speaking our minds and from encouraging others to speak theirs. Else this debate will be like a race run with bricks tied to the runners' an
kles. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Madame la Scientiste did not respond at once. "I\emdash  I'd like to help, but I'm not sure I can. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Voltaire spluttered with scorn. "I know enough of your procedures to know you can comply with my request. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "That poses no problem, true. But morally, I'm not at liberty to tamper with the Maid's program at whim. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Voltaire stiffened. "1 realize Madame has a low opinion of my philosophy, but surely\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Not so! I think the world of you! You have a modern mind, and from the depths of the dark past\emdash  astonishing. I wish the Empire had men like you! But}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 your point of view, though valid as far as it goes, is limited because of what it leaves out and cannot address. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "My philosophy? It embraces all, a universal view\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
"And I work for Artifice Associates and the Preservers, for Mr. Boker. I'm bound by ethics to give them the Maid they want. Unless I could convince them to delete the Maid's memory of her martyrdom, I can't do it. And Marq would have to get permission fro
m the company and the Skeptics to delete yours. He'd love to, I assure you. His Skeptics are more likely to consent than my Preservers. It would give you an advantage. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I quite agree, " he conceded at once. "Relieving me of my burdens without ridding the Maid of hers would not be rational or ethical. Neither Locke nor Newton would approve. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Madame la Scientiste did not answer at once. "I'll talk to my boss and to Monsieur Boker, " she said at last. "But I wouldn't hold my breath if I were you. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Voltaire smiled wryly and said, "Madame forgets I have no breath to hold. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
