\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He walked on, obliviously, while she stood with her mouth open. How could she read this man?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 15.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Unresponsive to the presence of Madame la Sorciere, the Maid sat upright in her cell, eyes closed. Warring voices pealed inside her head.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The noise was like the din of battle, chaotic and fierce. But if she listened intently, refusing to allow her immortal spirit to be ripped from her mortal flesh\emdash 
then, then, a divinely orchestrated polyphony would show her the rightful course.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The Archangel Michael, and St. Catherine, and St. Margaret\emdash from whose mouths her voices often spoke\emdash 
were reacting fiercely to her involuntary mastery of Monsieur Arouet's Complete Works. Particularly offensive to Michael was the Elements de Newton, whose philosophy Michael perceived to be incompatible with that of the Church\emdash 
indeed, with his own existence.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The Maid herself was not so sure. She found, to her surprise, a poetry and harmony in the equations}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 that proved\emdash as if proof were required\emdash the unsurpassed reality of the Creator, whose physical laws might be fathomable but whose purposes were not.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 How she knew these beauties was rather mysterious. She saw into the calculus of force and motion, the whirl of worlds. Like the lords and ladies at court, inert matter made its divinely orchestrated gavotte
. These things she sensed with her whole self, directly, as if penetrated by divine insight. Beauties arrived, out of pale air. How could she discount sublime perceptions?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Such divine invasion must be holy. That it came to her as a flood of memory, skills,
 associations, only proved further that it was heaven sent. La Sorciere murmured something about computer files and sub-Agents, but those were incantations, not truths.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Far more offensive to her than this new wisdom, far more, was that its author was an Englishman.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 'La }{\fs20 Henriade}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 . "}{\fs20  S}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 he told Michael, citing another of }{\fs20 Monsieur}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033  Aro}{\fs20 ue}
{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 t's wor}{\fs20 k}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 s, "is more repulsive }{\fs20 than Les Elements.}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033  How dare Monsieur Arouet, who }{\fs20 arrogantly}{
\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033  cal}{\fs20 ls}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033  himself by the false name \\nittiK, \bullet \bullet man that in England reason is free, w}{\fs20 hil}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 e in ou
r own beloved France, it's shackled to the dark imaginings of absolutist priests! Was it not }{\fs20 Jesuit}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033  priests who first taught this inquisitor how to reason?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 But what enraged the Maid most of all and made her thrash and strain at her chains\emdash until, fearing for her safety. La Sorciere freed her chafed ankles and wrists\emdash 
was his illegally printed, scurrilous poem about her. Villainous verse!}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 As soon as she was sure her voices had withdrawn, she waved a copy of 'La Pucelle' at the sorceress, incensed that the chaste Saints Catherine or Margaret\emdash who had momentarily vanished, but would surely return
\emdash might be forcibly exposed to}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 its lewdness. Both saints had already reproached her for her silly, girlish speculations about how attractive Monsieur Arouet might be\emdash what was she thinking?\emdash 
if he removed his ridiculous wig and lilac ribbons.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "How dare Monsieur Arouet represent me this way?" she railed, knowing full well that her stubborn refusal to call him Voltaire irked him no end. "He adds nine years to my
 age, dismisses my voices as outright lies. And slanders Baudricourt, who first enabled me to put before my king my vision for both him and France. A writer of preachy plays and irreverent slanders against the faithful, like Candide, he well may be
\emdash but that insufferable know-it-all calls himself a historian! If his other historical accounts are no more reliable than the one he gives of me, they and not my body deserve the fire. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The woman La Sorciere paled before this onslaught. These people\emdash if people they were at all, here in a byzantine, cloudy Purgatory\emdash 
backed away from the true ferocity of divine Purpose. Joan towered over the woman, with some relish.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Newton's clockwork wisdom is an intriguing vision of Creation's laws, " Joan thundered, "but Voltaire's history is a work of his imagination!\emdash  made up of three parts bile, two spleen. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 She raised her right arm in the same gesture she'd used to lead her soldiers and the knights of France into battle against the English king and his minions\emdash of whom, she now
 saw clearly, Monsieur Arouet de Voltaire was one. A warrior femme inspiratrice with an intense aversion to the kill, she now vowed all-out war against this, this\emdash 
she gasped in exasperation, "This nouveau riche bourgeois upstart darling of the aristocratic class, who's never known real want or need, and thinks horses are bred with carriages behind them. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Get him!" La Sorciere, ablaze with the Maid's fire, raged. "That's what we want!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Where is he?" demanded the Maid. "Where is this shallow little pissoir stream?\emdash that I may drown him in the depths of all I have suffered!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Oddly, La Sorciere seemed pleased by all this, as if it fit some design of her own.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 16.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Voltaire cackled with satisfaction. The cafe appeared, popping into luminous reality, independent of his human masters' consent or knowledge.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Subroutine accomplished, a small voice assured him. He made the cafe disappear and reappear three times more, to be sure that he had mastered the technique.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 What fools these rulers were, to think that they could m
ake the Great Voltaire a creature of their will! But now came the real test, the intricate procedure that would bring forth the Maid in all her womanly unfath-omability\emdash which, however, he was determined to fathom.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He had mastered the intricate logics of th
is place, given the capacities the man-scientist had given him. Did they think he was some animal, unable to apply blithe reason to their labyrinths of logic? He had found his way. traced the winding electronic pathways, devised the commands. Newton had b
een just as difficult, and he had encompassed that, had he not?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Now, the Maid. He did his digital dance, its logics, and\emdash }{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 She popped into the cafe.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You scum, " she said, lance drawn.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Not quite the greeting he'd expected. But then he saw the copy of 'La Pucelle' dangling on the point of her lance.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Cherie, " he cooed; whatever the offense, best to get in an apology early. "I can explain. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "That's your whole problem, " the Maid said. "Y
ou explain and explain and explain! Your plays are more tedious than the sermons I was forced to listen to in the cemetery at St. Ouen. Your railings against the sacred mysteries of the Church reveal a shallow, unfeeling mind bereft of awe and wonder. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You mustn't take it personally, " Voltaire pleaded. "It was directed at hypocritical reverence for you\emdash  and at the superstitions of religion. My friend, Thieriot\emdash 
he added passages more profane and obscene than any I had written. He needed money. He made a living reciting the poem in various salons. My poor virgin became an infamous whore, made to say gross and intolerable things. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The Maid did not lower her lance. Instead, she poked it several times against Voltaire's satin waist-coated chest.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Cherie, " he said. "If you knew how much I paid for this vest. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You mean, how much Frederick paid\emdash that pitiful, promiscuous, profligate pervert of a man. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Alliteration a bit heavy, " Voltaire said, "but otherwise, a quite nicely turned phrase. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 His newly gained s
kills meant he could divest her of her lance at once, squash it. But he preferred persuasiveness to force. He quoted, with some liberty, that pleasure-hating Christian, Paul: "When I was a child, I spoke as a child, thought as a child, behaved as a child.
 But when I became a woman, I put away manly things. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 She blinked. He remembered how her inquisitors had claimed that her acceptance of the gift of a fine cloak}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 was incompatible with the divine origin of her voices. In a whisk of lithe arms, Voltaire produced a Chantilly lace gown. Pop\emdash and a richly embroidered cloak.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You mock me, " the Maid said. But not before he saw a gleam of interest flare in her coal-dark eyes.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I long to see you as you are. " He held out the gown and cloak. "Your spirit I have no doubt is divine, but your natural form, like mine, is human; unlike mine, a woman's. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You think I could give up the freedom of a man for that?" She impaled the cloak and gown on the tip of her lance.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Not the freedom, " Voltaire said. "Just the armor and clothes. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 She fell silent, pensively gazing into the distance. The crowd on the street went about their business, walking by unconcerned. Obvious wallpaper, he thought; he would have to correct that.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Perhaps a trick. She was partial to miracles. "Another little trick I've learned since we last met. Voila. I can produce Gar9on. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Gar9on popped in out of nowhere, all four of his hands free. The Maid\emdash who had indeed once worked in a tavern, he recalled\emdash 
could not help it; she smiled. She also removed the gown and cloak from the lance, tossed the lance aside, and caressed the clothes.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He could not resist the impulse to quote himself.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "For I am man and justly proud}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 In human weakness to have part;}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Past mistresses have held my heart,}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 I'm happy still when thus aroused. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He fell to one knee before her. A grand gesture\emdash foolproof, in his experience.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Joan gaped, speechless.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Garcon placed both his right hands over the site where humans are supposed to have a heart. "Freedom such as yours, you offer? Monsieur,}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Mademoiselle, I appreciate your kindness, but I fear I must refuse. I cannot accept such a privilege for myself alone, while my fellows are doomed to toil in unsatisfying, dead-end jobs. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "He has a noble soul!" the Maid exclaimed.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Yes, but his brain leaves much to be desired. " Voltaire sucked reflectively at his teeth. "There has to be an underclass to do the dirty work of the elite. That is natural. Creating mechfolk of lim
ited intelligence is an ideal solution! Makes one wonder why, in all their history, no one made such an obvious step... "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "With all respect, " said Gar$on, "unless my meager understanding fails me, Monsieur and Mademoiselle are themselves nothing more than beings of limited intelligence, created by human masters to work for the elite. "
}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "What!" Voltaire's eyes widened.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "By what inherent right are you made more intelligent and privileged than I and others of my class? Do you have a soul? Should you be entitled to equal rights with humans, including the right to intermarry\emdash "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The Maid made a face. "Disgusting thought. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "\emdash to vote, to have equal access to the most sophisticated programming available?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "This machine man makes more sense than many dukes I've known, " said the Maid, thoughtfully furrowing her brow.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I shall not have two peasants contradict me, " said Voltaire. "The rights of man are one thing; the rights of the lower orders, another. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Garfon managed to exchange a look with the Maid. This instant\emdash before Monsieur, in a fit of pique, extinguished both her and Gar}{\fs20 c}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
on from the screen, displacing them to a gray holding space\emdash was retained in Ga}{\fs20 c}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 on's memory. Later, in his/its allowed interval for interior maintenance, the delicious moment reran again and again.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 17.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Marq tuned Nim in on the interoffice screen. "Did it! From now on, he'll be able to say anything he wants. I've deleted every scrape with authority he ever had. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Attaway, " said Nim, grinning.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Think I should delete run-ins with his father, too?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I'm not sure, " Nim said. "What were they like?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Pretty hot. His father was a strict disciplinarian, sympathetic to the 'Jansenist' view. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "What's that? A sports team?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I asked. He said, 'A Catholic version of a Protestant. ' I don't think they were teams. Something about sin being everywhere, pleasure's disgusting\emdash  usual primitive religion, Dark Ages stuff. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20 Nim}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033  grinned. "Most stuffs only disgusting when it's done right. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Marq laughed. "Too true. Still, maybe he first experienced the threat of censorship from his old man. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Nim paused to reflect. "You're worried about instabilities in the character-space, right?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Could happen. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "But you want killer instinct, right?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Marq nodded. "I can put in some editing algorithms to police instabilities. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Right. Not like you need him totally sane after the debate's over, or anything. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Might as well go for broke. Can't hurt. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Marq frowned. "I wonder... should we go through with this?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Hey, what choice we got? Junin Sector wants a trial of champions, we ship them one. Done deal. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "But if Imperial types come after us for illegal sims\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I like danger, passion, " Nim said. "You always agree, too. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Yes, but\emdash why are we getting smarter tiktoks now? They're not that hard to make. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Old prohibitions wearing out, my friend. And it has come up, many times. Just got knocked down, is all "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "By what?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Nim shrugged. "Politics, social forces\emdash who knows? I mean, people feel edgy about machines that think. Can't trust them. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "What if you couldn't even tell they were machines?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Huh? That's crazy. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Maybe a really smart machine doesn't want any competition. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Smarter than good ol' Marq? Doesn't exist. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "But they could... eventually. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Never. Forget it. Let's get to work. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 18.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Sybyl sat anxiously beside Monsieur Boker in the Great Coliseum. They were near the Imperial Gardens and an air of importance seemed to hover over everything.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 She could not stop tapping her nails\emdash her best full formal set\emdash 
on her knees. Among the murmur of four hundred thousand other spectators in the vast bowl, she anxiously awaited the appearance of the Maid and Voltaire on a gigantic screen.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Civilization, she thought, was a bit boring. Her time with the sims had opened her eyes to the force, the heady electricity, of the dark past. They had fought wars, slaughtered each other, all\emdash supposedly
\emdash for ideas.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Now, swaddled in Empire, humanity was soft. Instead of bloody battles, satisfyingly final, there were "fierce" trade wars, athletic head-buttings. And lately, a fashion for debates.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 This collision of sims, touted everywhere on Trantor, would be watched by over twenty billion households. And it was beamed to the entire Empire, wherever the creaky funnels of the wormho
le network went. The rude vigor of the prehistoric sims was undeniable; she felt it herself, a quickening in her pulse.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The merest few interviews and glimpses of the sims had intrigued the 3D audience. Those who brought up the age-old laws and prohibitions
 got shouted down. The air crackled with the zest for the new. No one had anticipated that this debate would balloon into this.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 This could spread. Within weeks, Junin could inflame all Trantor into a renaissance.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 And she was going to take every scrap of credit for it that she could, of course.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 She looked around at the president and other top-ranking executives of Artifice Associates, all chattering away happily.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The president, to demonstrate neutrality, sat between Sybyl and Marq\emdash who had not spoken to each other since the last meeting.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 On Marq's far side his client, the Skeptics' representative, scanned the program; next to him, Nim. Monsieur Boker gave Sybyl a nudge. "That can't be what I think it is, " he said.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Sybyl followed his eyes to a distant row at the back where what looked like a mechman sat quietly beside}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 a human girl. Only licensed mech vendors and bookies were allowed in the stadium. "Probably her servant, " Sybyl said. Minor infractions of the rules did not disturb her as they did Monsieur Boker
, who'd been especially testy since a 3D caster leaked the news that Artifice Associates was representing both the Preservers and Skeptics. Fortunately, the leak occurred too late for either party to do anything about it.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Mechserves aren't allowed, " Monsieur Boker observed.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Maybe she's handicapped, " Sybyl said to placate him. "Needs help in getting around. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "It won't understand what's going on anyway, " said Marq, directing his remark to Monsieur Boker. "They're truncated. Just a bunch of decision-making modules, really. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Precisely why it has no business here, " replied Monsieur Boker.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Marq beeped the arm of his chair and ostentatiously placed a bet on Voltaire to win.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "He's never won a bet in his whole life, " Sybyl told Monsieur Boker. "No head for the math. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Is that so?" Marq shot back, leaning forward to address Sybyl directly for the first time. "Why don't you put your money where your lovely mouth is?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I've got the probabilities on this one bracketed, " she said primly.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You couldn't solve the integral equation. " Marq snorted derisively.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Her nostrils flared. "A thousand. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Mere tokenism, " Marq chided her, "considering what you're being paid for this project. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "The same as you, " said Sybyl.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Will you two cut it out, " Nim said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Tell you what, " said Marq. "I'll bet my entire salary for the project on Voltaire. You bet yours on your anachronistic Maid. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Hey, " Nim said. "Hey. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
The president deftly addressed Marq's client, the Skeptic. "It's this keen competitive spirit that's made Artifice Associates the planet's leader in simulated intelligences. " Artfully he turned to the rival, Boker. "We try to\emdash "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You're on!" cried Sybyl.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Her dealings with the Maid had convinced her that the irrational must have a place in the human equation, too. She remained convinced for about three quick eye-blinks, and then began to doubt.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 9.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Voltaire loved audiences. And he had never appeared before one like this ocean of faces lapping at his feet.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Although tall in his former life, he felt that only now, gazing down at the multitudes from his hundred-meter height, had he achieved the stature he deserved. He patted his powdered wig and fussed with the sh
iny satin ribbon at his throat. With a gracious flourish of his hands, he made a deep bow to them, as if he'd already given the performance of his life. The crowd murmured like an awakening beast.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He glanced at the Maid, concealed from the audience behind a shimmering partition in the far corner of the screen. She folded her arms, pretending to be unimpressed.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Delay only excited the beast. He let the crowd cheer and stamp, ignoring boos and hisses from approximately half of those present.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 At least half of humanity has always been fools, he reflected. This was his first exposure to the advanced denizens of this colossal Empire. Millennia had made no difference.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He was not one to prematurely cut off adulation he knew was his due. Here he stood for the epitome of the French intellectual tradition, now vanquished but for him.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He gazed again at Joan\emdash who was, after all, the only other surviving member of their time, quite obviously the peak in human civilization. He whispered, "Tis our destiny to shine; theirs, to 
applaud. " When the moderator finally pleaded for silence\emdash a bit too soon; Voltaire would take that up with him later\emdash 
Voltaire endured Joan's introduction with what he hoped was a stoic smile. He elaborately insisted that Joan make her points first, only to have the moderator rather rudely tell him that here, they flipped a coin.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Voltaire won. He shrugged, then placed his hand over his heart. He began his recital in the declamatory style so dear to eighteenth-century Parisian hearts: no matter how defined th
e soul, like a deity, could not be shown to exist; its existence was inferred.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Truth of the inference lay beyond rational proof. Nor was there anything in Nature that required it.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 And yet, Voltaire continued to pontificate, there was nothing more obvious in Nature than the work of an intelligence greater than man's\emdash 
which man is able, within limits, to decipher. That man can decode Nature's secrets proved what the Church fathers and all the founders of the world's great religions had always said: that man's 
intelligence is a reflection of that same Divine Intelligence which authored Nature. Were this not so, natural philosophers could not}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 discern the laws behind Creation, either because there would be none, or because man would be so alien to them that he cou
ld not discern them. The very harmony between natural law, and our ability to discover it, strongly suggested that sages and priests of all persuasions are essentially correct!\emdash 
in arguing that we are but the creatures of an Almighty Power, whose Power is reflected in us. And this reflection in us of that Power may be justly termed our universal, immortal, yet individual souls.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You're praising priests!" the Maid exclaimed. She was swamped by the pandemonium that broke out in the crowd.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "The operation of chance, " Voltaire concluded, "in no way proves that Nature and Man\emdash who is part of Nature and as such a reflection of its Creator\emdash 
are somehow accidental. Chance is one of the principles through which natural law works. That principle may correspond with the t
raditional religious view that man is free to chart his own course. But this freedom, even when apparently random, obeys statistical laws in a way that man can comprehend. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The crowd muttered, confused. They needed an aphorism, he saw, to firm them up. Very well. "Uncertainty is certain, my friends. Certainty is uncertain. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Still they did not quiet, to better hear his words. Very well, again.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He clenched both fists and belted out in a voice of surprising bass power, "Man is, like Nature itself, free and determined both at once\emdash 
as religious sages have been telling us for centuries though, to be sure, they use a different vocabulary, far less precise than ours. Much mischief and misunderstanding between religion and science stem from that.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I've been greatly misunderstood, " Voltaire resumed. "I'd like to take this opportunity to apologize}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 for distortions resulting because all I said and wrote focused only on errors of faith, not on its intuited truths. But I lived during an era in which errors of faith were 
rife, while reason's voice had to fight to be heard. Now, the opposite appears to be true. Reason mocks faith. Reason shouts while faith whispers. As the execution of France's greatest and most faithful heroine proved\emdash 
" a grand, sweeping gesture to Joan "\emdash faith without reason is blind. But, as the superficiality and vanity of much of my life and work prove, reason without faith is lame. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Some who had booed and hissed now blinked, mouths agape\emdash and then cheered... while, he noticed, those who had applauded, now booed and hissed. Voltaire stole a look at the Maid.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 20.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Far below in the rowdy crowd, Nim turned to Marq. "What?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Marq was ashen. "Damned if I know. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Yeah, " Nim said, "maybe literally. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Divinity won't be mocked!" Monsieur Boker cried out. "Faith shall prevail!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Voltaire was relinquishing the podium to his rival, to the amazed delight of the Preservers. Their shouts were equaled by the horrified disbelief of Skeptics.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Marq recalled the words he had spoken at the meeting. He muttered, "Voltaire, divested of his anger at authority, is and is not Voltaire. " He turned to Monsieur Boker. "My Lord!\emdash you may be right. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "No, my Lord!" snapped Monsieur Boker. "He is never wrong. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The Maid surveyed the masses of this Limbo from her high angle. Strange small vessels for souls they were, swaying below like wheat in a summer storm.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Monsieur is absolutely right!" she thundered across the stadium. "Nothing in nature is more obvious than that both nature and man do indeed possess a soul!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Skeptics hooted. Preservers cheered. Others\emdash who equated the belief that nature has a soul with paganism, she saw in a flash\emdash scowled, suspecting a trap.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Anyone who has seen the countryside near my home village, Domremy, or the great marbled church at Rouen will testify that nature, the creation of an awesome power, and man, the creator of marvels\emdash 
 such as this place, of magical works\emdash both possess intense consciousness, a soul!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 She waved a gentle hand at him while the mass\emdash  did the size of them betray how tiny were their souls?\emdash calmed themselves.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "But what my brilliant friend has not addressed is how the fact of the soul relates to the question at hand: whether clockwork intelligences, such as his own, possess a soul. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The crowd stamped, booed, cheered, hissed, and roared. Objects the Maid could not identify sailed through the air. Police officers appeared to pull some men and women, who appeared to be having fits, or else sudden
 divine visitations, from the crowd.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "The soul of man is divine!" she cried out.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Screams of approval, shouts of denial.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "It is immortal!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The din was so great people covered their ears with their hands to muffle the noise, of which they themselves were the source.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 175}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "And unique, " Voltaire whispered. "/ certainly am. And you. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "It is unique!" she shouted, eyes ablaze. Voltaire shot to his feet beside her. "I agree!" The congregation frothed over, like a pot left to boil, she observed.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The Maid ignored th
e raving masses at her enormous feet. She regarded Voltaire with bemused, affectionate doubt. She yielded the floor. Voltaire had a lust for the last word. He began to speak of his hero, Newton. "No, no, " she interrupted. "That isn't what the formulas ar
e at all!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Must you embarrass me in front of the largest audience I've ever known?" Voltaire whispered. "Let us not squabble over algebra, when we must\emdash " he narrowed his eyes significantly "\emdash 
calculate. " Sulking, he yielded the floor to her.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Calculus, " she corrected. But softly, so that only he could hear. "It's not the same thing at all. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 To her own astonishment and the rising hysteria of the crowd, she found herself explaining the philosophy of the digital Self\emdash all with a fiery passion she'd not known 
since spurring her horse into sacred battle. In the beseeching sea of wide eyes below her, she felt the need of this place and time, for ardor and conviction.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Incredible. " Voltaire clicked his tongue. "That you of all people should have a talent for mathematics. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "The Host gave it unto me, " she replied, above the raucous fray.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Ignoring shouts, the Maid noticed again the figure so somehow like Gar?on in the crowd. She could barely make him out from such a distance, despite her immense height. Yet she fel
t he was watching her the way she'd watched Bishop Cauchon, the most vile and relentless of her}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 oppressors. (A cool, sublime truth intruded: the good bishop, at the end, must have been touched by divinity's grace and Christ's merciful compassion, for she r
ecalled no harm coming to her as a result of her trial.... )}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Her attention snapped back to the howling masses, the distant... man. This figure was not human in essence, she felt. It looked like a man, but her sensitive programs told her otherwise.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 But what could he\emdash it\emdash be?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Suddenly a great light blared before her eyes. All three of her voices spoke, clear and hammering, even above the din. She listened, nodded.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "It is true, " she addressed the crowd, trusting the voices to speak through her, "that on
ly the Almighty can make souls! But just so Christ, out of his infinite love and compassion, could not deny a soul to clockwork beings. To all. " She had to shout her final words over the roaring crowd. "Even wig-makers!"}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Heretic!" someone yelled.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You're muddying the question!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Traitor!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Another cried out, "The original sentence was right! She ought to be burned at the stake again!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Again?" the Maid echoed. She turned to Voltaire. "What do they mean, again?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Voltaire casually brushed a speck of lint fro
m his embroidered satin waistcoat. "I haven't the slightest idea. You know how fanciful and perverse human beings are. " With a sly wink, he added, "Not to mention, irrational. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 His words calmed her, but she had lost sight of the strange man.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 21.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I cheated?" Marq shouted to Sybyl. The coliseum crowd seethed. "Joan of Arc explaining computational metaphysics? / cheated?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You started it!" Sybyl said. "You think I don't know when my office has been rigged? You think you're dealing with an amateur?" "Well, I\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "\emdash and I don't know a character-constraint matrix when I find one glued into my Joan sim?" "No, I\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You think I'm not as bright?" "This is scandalous!" said Monsieur Boker. "What did you do? It's enough to make me believe in witchcraft!" "You mean to sa
y you don't?" Marq's client said, ever the Skeptic. He and Boker began to argue, adding to the indignant shouts of the crowd, now waxing hysterical.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The president of Artifice Associates, rubbing his temples, murmured, "Ruined. We're ruined. We'll never be able to explain. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
Sybyl's attention was diverted. The mechman she had noticed earlier, holding his honey-haired, human companion's hand, rushed down the aisle toward the screen. As it passed by, one of its three free hands happened to brush her skirt. "Pa
rdon, " it said, pausing just long enough for Sybyl to read the mechstamp on its chest.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Did that thing dare to touch you?" Monsieur Boker asked. His face swelled with rage.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "No, no, nothing like that, " Sybyl said. The mechman, pulling his human companion with him, fled toward the screen.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Do you know it?" Marq asked.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "In a way, " Sybyl replied. In the cafe/sim she had modeled the Garcon 213-ADM interactive character after it. Laziness, perhaps, had led her to simply holo-copy the physical appearance of a 
standard tiktok-form. Like all artists, sim-programmers borrowed from life; they didn't create it.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
