\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 In fact, Hari was beginning to doubt whether the stiff, formal scientific establishment was worthy of high regard any longer. All around him he saw corruption of the impartiality of science, f
rom the boons-manship networking to the currying of Imperial scraps which passed for a promotion system.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Just yesterday he had been visited by a Dean of Adjustments who had advised, with oily logic, that Hari use some of his Imperial power to confer a boon
 upon a professor who had done very little work, but who had family ties to the High Council.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The dean had said quite sincerely, "Don't you think it is in the better interests of the university that you grant a small boon to one with influence?" When Hari 
did not, he nonetheless called the fellow to tell him why.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The dean was astonished with such honesty. Only later did Hari decide that the dean was right, within his own logic system. If boons were mere benefits, simple largess, then
 why not confer them wholly on political grounds? It was an alien way of thinking, but consistent, he had to admit.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari sighed. When Yugo paused in his vehement tirade, Hari smiled. No, wrong response. A worried frown\emdash there, that did it. Yugo launched bac
k into rapid talk, arms taking wing, epithets stacked to improbable heights.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari realized that the mere exposure to politics as it truly was, the brutal struggle of blind swarms in shadow, had raised doubts about 'his own, rather smug, positions. Was the 
science he had so firmly believed in back on Helicon truly as useful to people like the Dahlites as he imagined?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 So his musing came around to his equations: Could the Empire ever be driven by reason and moral decision, rather than power and wealth? Theocra
cies had tried, and failed. Scientocracies, rather more rarely, had been too rigid to last.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
