\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Afraid I don't go back that far, " Hari said, signing off. "Enjoy the work. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 18.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He and Dors watched the great luminous spiral turn beneath them in its eternal night.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I do appreciate such perks, " she said dreamily. They stood alone before the spectacle. Worlds and lives and stars, all like crushed diamonds thrown against eternal blackness.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Getting into the palace just to look at the Emperor's display rooms?" He had ordered all the halls cleared.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Getting away from snoopers and eavesdroppers. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You... you haven't heard from\emdash ?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 She shook her head. "Daneel pulled nearly all the rest of us off Trantor. He says little to me. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I'm pretty damn sure the alien minds won't strike again. They're afraid of robots. It took me a while to see that lay behind their talk about revenge. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Mingled hate and fear. Very human. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Still, I think they've had their revenge. They say the Galaxy was lush with life before we came. There are cycles of barren eras, then luxuri
ant ones. Don't know why. Apparently that's happened several times before, at intervals of a third of a billion years\emdash great diebacks of intelligent life, leaving only spores. Now }{\fs20 The}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
y've come to our Mesh and become digital fos-}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20 sils"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Fossils don't kill, " she said sardonically.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Not as well as we do, apparently. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Not you\emdash us. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "They do hate you robots. Not that they have any love of humans\emdash after all, we made you, long ago. We're to blame. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "They are so strange.... "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
He nodded. "I believe they'll stay in their digital preserve until Marq and Sybyl can get them transported into their ancient spore state. They once lived that way for longer than the Galaxy takes to make a rotation. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Your 'pretty damn sure' isn't good enough for Daneel, " she said. "He wants them exterminated. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "It's a standoff. If Daneel goes after them, he'll have to pull the plug on Tranter's Mesh. That will wound the Empire. So he's stuck, fuming but impotent. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I hope you have estimated the balance properly, " she said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
A glimmering, gossamer thought flitted across his mind. The tiktok attacks upon the Lamurk faction had discredited them in public opinion. Now they would be suppressed throughout the Galaxy. And in time, the meme-minds would leave Trantor.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari frowned. Daneel surely wanted both these outcomes.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He had undoubtedly suspected that the meme-minds had survived, perhaps that they were in action on Trantor. So could Hari's amateur maneuverings, including the Lamurk murders, have been deftly
 conjured up by Daneel? Could a robot so accurately predict what he, Hari, would do?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 A chill ran through him. Such ability would be breathtaking. Superhuman.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 With tiktoks now soon to be suppressed, Trantor would have trouble producing its own food. Tasks once done by men would have to be re-learned, taking}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 generations to establish such laborers as a socially valued group again. Meanwhile, dozens of other worlds would have to send Trantor food, a lifeline slender and vulnerable. Did Daneel intend that, too? To what end?
}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari felt uneasy. He sensed social forces at work, just beyond his view.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
Was such adroit thinking the product of millennia of experience and high, positronic intelligence? For just a moment, Hari had a vision of a mind both strange and measureless, in human terms. Was that what an immortal machine became?}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Then he pushed the idea away. It was too unsettling to contemplate. Later, perhaps, when psy-chohistory was done...}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He noticed Dors staring at him. What had she said? Oh, yes...}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Estimating the balance, yes. I'm getting the feel for these things. With Voltaire and Joan doing the scut work, and Yugo now chairman of the Mathist Department, I actually have time to think. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "And suffer fools gladly?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "The Academic Potentate? At least I understand her now. " He peered at Dors. "Daneel says he will leave Trantor. He's lost a lot of his humani-forms. Does he need you?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 She looked up at him in the soft glow. Her expression worked with conflict. "I can't leave you. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "His orders?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Mine. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He gritted his teeth. "The robots who died\emdash you knew them?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Some. We trained together back, back when... "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You don't have to conceal anything from me. I know you must be at least a century old. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Her mouth made an O of surprise, then quickly closed. "How?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You know more than you should. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "So do you\emdash in bed, anyway. " She chuckled.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I learned it from a pan I met. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 She laughed bawdily, then sobered. "I'm one hundred sixty-three. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "With the thighs of a teenager. If you had tried to leave Trantor, I'd have blocked you. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 She blinked. "Truly?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He bit his lip, thinking. "Well, no. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 She smiled. "More romantic to say yes... "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I have a habit of honesty\emdash which I'd better drop if I want to stay First Minister. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "So you would let me go? You still feel that you owe that to Daneel?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "If he thought the danger to you was that great, then I would honor his judgment. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You still respect us so?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Robots work selflessly for the Empire\emdash always. Few humans do. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You don't wonder what we did to earn the aliens' revenge?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Of course. Do you know?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 She shook her head, gazing out at the vast turning disk.
 Suns of blue and crimson and yellow swept along their orbits amid dark dust and disorder. "It was something awful. Daneel was there and he will not speak of it. There is nothing in our history of this. I've looked. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "An empire lasting many millennia has manifold secrets. " Hari watched the slow spin of a hundred billion flaming stars. "I'm more interested in its future\emdash in saving it. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You fear that future, don't you?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Terrible things are coming. The equations show that. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "We can face them together. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He took her in his arms, but they both still}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20 w}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 atched the Galaxy's shining marvels. "I dream of rounding something, a way to help the Empire, even}{\fs20  after}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033  tier we're gone.... "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "And you fear something, too, " she said into his neck.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "How did you know? Yes\emdash I fear the chaos that could come from so many forces, divergent vector turmoil\emdash 
all acting to bring down the order of the Empire. I fear for the very... " His face clouded. "For die very foundations themselves. Foundations... "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Chaos comes?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I know we ourselves, our minds, come out of skating on the inner rim of chaos-states. The digital}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20 w}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 orld shows that. You show that. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 She said soberly, "I do not think positronic minds understand themselves any better than human ones. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "We\emdash our minds and our Empire\emdash both spring from an emergent order of inner, basically chaotic states, but... "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You do not want the Empire to crash from such chaos. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I want the Empire to survive! Or at least, if it falls, to reemerge. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari suddenly felt the pain of such vast movements. The Empire was like a mind, and minds sometimes went crazy, crashed. A disaster for one solitary mind. How colossally worse for an Empire.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Seen through the prism of his mathematics, humanity was on a long march pressing forward through surrounding dark. Time battered them with storms, rewarded them with sunshine\emdash 
and they did not glimpse that these passing seasons came from the shifting cadences of huge, eternal equations.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Running the equations time-forward, then backward, Hari had seen humanity's mortal parade in snips. Somehow that made it oddly touching. Steeped in their own eras, few worlds ever glimpsed}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 the route ahead. There was no shortage of portentous talk, or of oafs who pretended with a wink and a nod to fathom the unseeable. Misled, whole Zones stumbled and fell.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He sought patterns, but beneath those vast sweeps lay the seemingly infinitesimal, living people. Across the realm of stars, under the laws that reigned like gods, lay innumerable lives i
n the process of being lost. For to live was to lose, in the end.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Social laws acted and people were maimed, damaged, robbed, and strangled by forces they could not even glimpse. People were driven to sickness, to desperation, to loneliness and fear and rem
orse. Shaken by tears and longing, in a world they fundamentally failed to fathom, they nonetheless carried on.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 There was nobility in that. They were fragments adrift in time, motes in an Empire rich and strong and full of pride, an order failing and battered and hollow with its own emptiness.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 With leaden certainty, Hari at last saw that he probably would not be able to rescue the great ramshackle Empire, a beast of fine nuance and multiplying self-delusions.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 No savior, he. But perhaps he could help.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 They b
oth stood in silence for a long, aching time. The Galaxy turned in its slow majesty. A nearby fountain spewed glorious arcs into the air. The waters seemed momentarily free, but in fact were trapped forever within the steel skies of Trantor. As was he.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Har
i felt a deep emotion he could not define. It tightened his throat and made him press Dors to him. She was machine and woman and... something more. Another element he could not fully know, and he cherished her all the more for that.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You care so much, " Dors whispered.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I have to. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Perhaps we should try to simply live more, worry less. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He kissed her fervently and then laughed. "Quite right. For who knows what the future may bring?" Very slowly, he winked at her.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 AFTERWORD}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The Foundation series began in 
World War II, as America arced toward its zenith as a world power. The series played out over decades as the United States dominated the world's matters in a fashion no other nation ever had. Yet the Foundation is about imperium and decline. Did this betr
ay an anxiety, born even in the moment of approaching glory?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 I had always wondered if this was so. Part of me itched to explore the issues which lace the series.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The idea of writing further novels in the Foundation universe came from Janet Asimov and the As
imov estate's representative, Ralph Vicinanza. Approached by them, I at first declined, being busy with physics and my own novels. But my subconscious, once aroused, refused to let go the notion. After half a year of struggling with ideas plainly made for
 
the Foundation, persistently demanding expression, I finally called up Ralph Vicinanza and began putting together a plan to construct a fittingly complex curve of action and meaning, to be revealed in several novels. Though we spoke to several authors abo
ut this project, the best suited seemed two hard SF writers broadly influenced by Asimov and of unchallenged technical ability: Greg Bear and David Brin.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Bear, Brin, and I have kept in close touch while I wrote this first volume, for we intend to create thr
ee stand-alone novels which nonetheless carry forward an overarching mystery to its end. Elements of this make their first appearance here, to amplify further through Greg Bear's Foundation and Chaos, finding completion in Erin's Third Foundation. (These 
are preliminary titles. ) I have planted in the narrative prefiguring details and key elements which shall bear later fruit.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Genres are constrained conversations. Constraint is essential, defining the rules and assumptions open to an author. If hard SF occu
pies the center of science fiction, that is probably because hardness gives the firmest boundary. Science itself yields crisp confines.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Genres are also like immense discussions, with ideas developed, traded, mutated, their variations spun down through time. Players ring changes on each other\emdash 
more tike a steppin'out jazz band than a solo concert in a plush auditorium. Contrast "serious" fiction (mote accurately described, in my eyes, as merely se}{\fs20 lf}{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
-consciously solemn). It has canonical classics that supposedly stand outside of time, deserving awe, looming great and intact by themselves.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Much of the pleasure of mysteries, of espionage novels or SF, lies in the interaction of writers with each other and, particularly in SF's invention of fan-dom, with the reade
rs as well. This isn't a defect; it's the essential nature of popular culture, which the United States has dominated in our age, with the invention of jazz, rock, the musical, and written genres such as the Western, the hardboiled detective, modern fantas
y, and other rich areas. Many kinds of SF (hard, Utopian, military, satirical) share}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 assumptions, code words, lines of argument, narrative voices. Fond remembrance of golden age Astounding and its letter column, of the New Wave, of Horace Gold's Galaxy\emdash thes
e are echoes of distant conversations earnestly carried out.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Genre pleasures are many, but this quality of shared values within an ongoing discussion may be the most powerful, enlisting lifelong devotion in its fans. In contrast to the Grand Canon view of 
great works standing like monoliths in a deserted landscape, genre reading satisfactions are a striking facet of modern democratic (pop) culture, a shared movement.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 There are questions about how writers deal with what some call the "anxiety of influence, " but which I'd prefer to term more mildly: the digestion of tradition.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 I'm reminded of John Berger's definition of hack work, describing oil 
painting in Ways of Seeing, as "... not the result of either clumsiness or provincialism; it is the result of the market making more insistent demands than the art. " Fair enough; but this can happen in any context. Working in a known region of concept-sp
ace does not necessarily imply that the territory has been mined out. Nor is fresh ground always fertile.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Surely we should notice that a novel Hemingway thought the best in American literature is a sequel\emdash  indeed, following on a boy's book, Tom Sawyer.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Shar
ing common ground isn't only a literary tradition. Are we thrown into moral confusion when we hear Rhapsody on a Theme by Paganini? Do we indignantly march from the concert hall when assaulted by Variations on a Theme by Haydn? Sharecropping by the Greats
? Shocking!}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Reinspecting the assumptions and methods of classical works can yield new fruit. Fresh narrative can both strike out into new territory while reflecting on}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 the landscape of the past. Recall that Hamlet drew from several earlier plays about the same plot.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
Isaac himself revisited the Foundation, taking different angles of attack each time. In the beginning, psychohistory equated the movements of people as a whole with the motions of molecules. The Second Foundation looked at perturbations to such d
eterministic laws (the Mule) and implied that only a superhuman elite could manage instabilities. Later, robots emerged as the elite, better than humans at dispassionate government. Beyond robots came Gaia... and so on.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 In this three-book series we shall reinspect the role of robots, and what psychohistory might look like as a theory. More riffs upon the basic tune.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
